placebos have on the body.

20:23.809 --> 20:27.350
Getting a placebo treatment
can have surprisingly
large effects

20:27.433 --> 20:29.558
on depression, and anxiety,

20:29.642 --> 20:32.308
and even some
neurological disorders,
like Parkinson's disease.

20:33.142 --> 20:35.101
We are studying
placebo effects

20:35.184 --> 20:37.892
to understand
the brain mechanisms

20:37.976 --> 20:39.892
that allow that kind
of response to work.

20:39.976 --> 20:43.934
Duboc:
The test he's doing
on me today is based
on pain sensitivity,

20:44.017 --> 20:46.226
via a device that will
safely burn my skin.

20:46.308 --> 20:48.892
Ow, ow, ow, ow, ow!
Stop, stop, stop!

20:48.976 --> 20:52.267
Three separate spots on my
arm were covered in cream.

20:52.350 --> 20:55.226
I was told the center one
was painkilling lidocaine,

20:55.308 --> 20:57.767
while the outer two
were merely moisturizer.

20:58.350 --> 20:59.934
All three spots were
then burned,

21:00.017 --> 21:03.226
and I was asked to rate
the pain level of each.

21:03.308 --> 21:05.059
-The first one was
the most painful.
-Mm-hmm.

21:05.142 --> 21:06.600
The last one was
the second most painful,

21:06.684 --> 21:08.059
and the middle one,

21:08.142 --> 21:10.642
with the lidocaine,
was the least painful.

21:10.725 --> 21:13.600
The thing is because you knew
this was a placebo study,

21:13.684 --> 21:15.267
-we double-crossed you.

21:15.350 --> 21:17.976
-So, these were both
moisturizer cream.

21:18.059 --> 21:19.976
So, in this case,
you had a little bit less pain

21:20.059 --> 21:22.809
with the placebo than
with the actual lidocaine.

21:22.892 --> 21:26.101
And that's in part because
you expected it to be lower.

21:26.184 --> 21:28.600
So, why did that happen?

21:28.684 --> 21:31.600
Placebo treatments
can activate

21:31.684 --> 21:33.892
the brain systems in
the prefrontal cortex,

21:33.976 --> 21:36.558
that are really important
for assignment of meaning.

21:36.642 --> 21:37.892
In addition, we're seeing

21:37.976 --> 21:39.433
activation of
pathways that connect

21:39.517 --> 21:41.101
the frontal cortex
to the brainstem.

21:41.184 --> 21:43.267
And so, what we're finding
is that a placebo treatment

21:43.350 --> 21:46.600
can tap into that system,
and can activate

21:46.684 --> 21:49.059
natural pain-relieving
chemicals in your brain.

21:49.142 --> 21:51.684
Can you give some
examples of ways that

21:51.767 --> 21:54.642
placebo works in
alternative medicine?

21:54.725 --> 21:56.433
A big part,
I think, of

21:56.517 --> 21:59.184
how people progress
over time with illness

21:59.267 --> 22:02.142
is their narrative for
what that illness is.

22:02.226 --> 22:04.184
What caused it?
What's gonna help me?

22:04.267 --> 22:06.017
Is there help?
Is there hope?

22:06.101 --> 22:07.475
I think,
to the degree

22:07.558 --> 22:09.184
that alternative
medicine treatments

22:09.267 --> 22:12.142
work that don't have any real
physiological mechanisms,

22:12.226 --> 22:15.350
they work by helping people
to change that narrative.

22:15.433 --> 22:17.767
And if people
feel better

22:17.850 --> 22:19.809
after taking
some substance,

22:19.892 --> 22:22.308
that could be caused
by the placebo effect,

22:22.392 --> 22:24.642
in which case,
it's not

22:24.725 --> 22:27.017
the thing that you're
taking that's helping you.

22:27.101 --> 22:28.767
It's you helping you.

22:28.850 --> 22:30.850
Duboc:
And, as it turns out,

22:30.934 --> 22:34.684
helping people help themselves
is a pretty lucrative busines.

22:34.767 --> 22:36.725
